Brexit, and after?
NEW YORK – It will take a lot of time for the United Kingdom, Europe, and the rest of the world to digest the implications of the Brexit referendum conducted by the UK.
The most profound consequences will, of course, depend on the EU's response to the UK's withdrawal.
The majority of people initially believed that the EU would not "cut off the branch it was sitting on": after all, a friendly divorce seemed to be in everyone's interest.
But the divorce – as is often the case – could become complicated.
Integration commercially and economically between the UK and the EU is mutually beneficial, and if the EU were to take seriously its belief that more economic integration is desirable, its leaders would seek to ensure that the links remain as close as possible given the circumstances.
Yet, Jean-Claude Juncker, the architect of massive corporate tax avoidance strategies for companies based in Luxembourg and now President of the European Commission, seems to adopt a hard-line stance: "Out means out," he has said.
This knee-jerk reaction may be understandable, given that Juncker could be seen as presiding over the first step in the dissolution of the EU.
He argues that to discourage other countries from leaving, the EU must not accept any compromises, offering the UK barely more than what it guarantees under World Trade Organization agreements.
In other words, Europe should not be kept united by the benefits it offers its members, which far outweigh its costs.
The economic prosperity, sense of solidarity, and pride in being European are not enough, according to Juncker.
No, Europe must be maintained by threats, intimidation, and fear.
This position does not take into account a lesson that is clearly apparent both in the vote for Brexit and in the Republican primaries in the United States: a large part of the population has suffered greatly in recent times.
The neoliberal agenda of the last four decades may have been good for the top 1%, but not for the rest of the population.
I had predicted for a long time that this stagnation would eventually have political consequences.
This day has now arrived.
On both sides of the Atlantic, citizens consider that trade agreements are the source of their misfortunes.
Although this is an excessive oversimplification, it is understandable.
Today's trade agreements are negotiated in secret, ensuring good representation of business interests but excluding ordinary citizens or workers entirely.
Not surprisingly, the results have been one-sided: the negotiating position of workers has weakened further, exacerbating the effects of legislation that diminishes union power and employee rights.
Although trade agreements have played a role in creating these inequalities, many other factors have contributed to tilting the political balance in favor of capital.
For example, intellectual property rules have increased the power of pharmaceutical companies to raise drug prices.
Indeed, any increase in market power of businesses in fact implies a decrease in real wages – an increase in inequalities that has become a characteristic of most advanced countries today.
In many sectors, industrial concentration is on the rise – and so is market power.
The effects of stagnation and falling real wages have been added to those of austerity, which threatened cuts in public services that so many low- and middle-income workers depend on.
The economic uncertainty this results in for workers, when combined with migration, has created a toxic mix.
Many refugees are victims of wars and oppression to which the West has contributed.
Providing aid is a moral responsibility for all, but especially for former colonial powers.
And yet, despite the fact that many would likely deny it, an increase in the supply of unskilled labor – as long as we are dealing with normal negatively sloped demand curves – leads to a decrease in equilibrium wages.
And when wages cannot fall, unemployment rises.
This is especially worrying in countries where poor economic management has already led to a high level of overall unemployment.
Europe, particularly the Eurozone, has been very poorly managed over the past few decades to the point that its average unemployment rate is now two digits.
Unrestricted migration in Europe means that the countries which have succeeded better in reducing unemployment will inevitably end up hosting more than their fair share of refugees.
The workers in these countries bear the cost of depressed wages and higher unemployment, while employers benefit from cheaper labor.
The burden of refugees, as expected, falls on those least able to bear it.
Certainly, there are many discussions about the net benefits of immigration.
For a country offering a low level of guaranteed social benefits – social security, education, healthcare, etc. – to all its citizens, this might be the case.
But for countries providing a decent social safety net, the opposite is true.
The result of all this downward pressure on wages and cuts to public services has been the hollowing out of the middle class, with similar consequences on both sides of the Atlantic.
Middle-class and working-class households have not benefited from economic growth.
They know that banks caused the 2008 crisis; but they have then seen billions allocated to save the banks, and negligible amounts to save their homes and jobs.
While the median real (inflation-adjusted) income for a full-time male worker in the United States is lower than it was four decades ago, the electorate's anger should surprise no one.
Moreover, politicians who promised change did not meet expectations.
Ordinary citizens knew the system was unfair, but they began to see it as even more rigged than they had imagined, thus losing the little trust they still had in the ability or willingness of traditional political figures to fix it.
This too is understandable: the new politicians shared the perspective of those who had promised that globalization would benefit everyone.
However, a vote of anger does not solve problems, and may in fact lead to a political and economic situation that is even worse.
The same applies if one responds with anger to a vote.
Forgetting the past is a basic principle in economics.
On both sides of the Channel, politics must now seek to understand how, in a democracy, the political establishment managed to do so little to address the concerns of many citizens.
Now, each EU government must consider improving the well-being of ordinary citizens as its primary objective.
More neoliberal ideology will not help.
And we should stop confusing objectives and means: for example, free trade, if well-managed, could bring greater shared prosperity; but if poorly managed, it will certainly reduce the standard of living for many – perhaps the majority – of citizens.
There are alternatives to current neoliberal policies that can create shared prosperity, just as there are alternatives – such as the Transatlantic Trade and Investment Partnership proposed by U.S. President Barack Obama with the EU – that would cause much more harm.
The challenge today is to learn from the past, so as to adopt the former and avoid the latter.
